export const QUESTION_BANK = [
  {"num":1,"stem":"An RBT is working with a client who engages in hand-flapping. The BCBA asks the RBT to record every instance of hand-flapping during a 30-minute session. Which measurement procedure should the RBT use?","options":["Duration recording","Frequency/event recording","Whole interval recording","Momentary time sampling"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Frequency (event) recording involves counting each discrete occurrence of a behavior, which is appropriate when the behavior has a clear beginning and end and when the goal is to count every instance. Duration recording measures how long a behavior lasts, not how many times it occurs. Whole interval recording scores whether the behavior occurred throughout an entire interval. Momentary time sampling only checks whether the behavior is occurring at the end of each interval.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.1","id":1},
  {"num":2,"stem":"An RBT is collecting data on how long a child engages in tantrum behavior from the moment the tantrum starts until it stops. Which type of measurement is the RBT using?","options":["Latency recording","Frequency recording","Duration recording","Partial interval recording"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Duration recording measures the total amount of time a behavior occurs from onset to offset. Latency recording measures the time between a stimulus and the onset of the behavior. Frequency recording counts the number of occurrences. Partial interval recording only notes whether a behavior occurred at any point during an interval.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.1","id":2},
  {"num":3,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to measure how long it takes a student to begin working on a task after the teacher gives the instruction. Which measurement procedure is most appropriate?","options":["Latency recording","Inter-response time recording","Duration recording","Frequency recording"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Latency recording measures the elapsed time between a stimulus (the teacher's instruction) and the initiation of the response (beginning to work). Inter-response time (IRT) measures the time between two consecutive occurrences of the same behavior. Duration recording measures how long a behavior lasts once it starts. Frequency recording counts the number of times a behavior occurs.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.1","id":3},
  {"num":4,"stem":"An RBT is observing a student during a 20-minute independent work period. The RBT divides the time into 1-minute intervals and records whether the student is on-task at the exact moment each interval ends. What type of recording is this?","options":["Whole interval recording","Partial interval recording","Momentary time sampling","Continuous recording"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Momentary time sampling (MTS) involves observing only at the end of each interval and recording whether the behavior is occurring at that exact moment. Whole interval recording requires the behavior to occur throughout the entire interval. Partial interval recording scores whether the behavior occurred at any point during the interval. Continuous recording tracks every instance of the behavior.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.2","id":4},
  {"num":5,"stem":"An RBT completed a session and is entering data into the client's data tracking system. The RBT realizes they forgot to record data for one of the target behaviors during the session. What should the RBT do?","options":["Estimate the data based on memory and enter it into the system","Leave the data field blank and inform the supervisor","Copy data from the previous session to fill in the gap","Ask a colleague who was not present to estimate the data"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When data is missed, the RBT should not fabricate or estimate data. The appropriate action is to leave the field blank and inform the supervisor so they are aware of the gap. Estimating data from memory is unreliable. Copying previous session data is falsifying records. A colleague who was not present cannot provide accurate data.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.4","id":5},
  {"num":6,"stem":"An RBT is collecting data on a client's completed math worksheets at the end of each session. Which type of measurement is the RBT using?","options":["Frequency recording","Permanent product recording","Duration recording","Whole interval recording"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Permanent product recording involves measuring the tangible outcomes or products of a behavior (completed worksheets) rather than directly observing the behavior as it occurs. Frequency recording involves counting each instance of a behavior in real time. Duration recording measures how long a behavior lasts. Whole interval recording is a time-based observation method.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.3","id":6},
  {"num":7,"stem":"An RBT is graphing data for a client's target behavior. The BCBA instructs the RBT to plot the number of correct responses on the vertical axis and the session number on the horizontal axis. Which component of a graph does the vertical axis represent?","options":["The independent variable","The dependent variable","The phase change line","The trend line"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The vertical axis (y-axis) of a graph represents the dependent variable, which is the behavior being measured. The independent variable is typically represented by phase labels or condition changes. A phase change line is a vertical dashed line indicating a change in conditions. A trend line is drawn through data points to show the direction of change.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.4","id":7},
  {"num":8,"stem":"During a session, an RBT divides a 10-minute observation into 30-second intervals. If the target behavior occurs at any point during an interval, the RBT marks that interval as having the behavior. Which recording method is this?","options":["Momentary time sampling","Whole interval recording","Partial interval recording","Event recording"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Partial interval recording involves dividing an observation period into intervals and recording whether the behavior occurred at any point during each interval. Momentary time sampling only checks if the behavior is happening at the exact end of each interval. Whole interval recording requires the behavior to occur throughout the entire interval. Event recording counts every discrete instance.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.2","id":8},
  {"num":9,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to measure the amount of time between the end of one vocal outburst and the beginning of the next. Which measurement procedure should the RBT use?","options":["Duration recording","Frequency/event recording","Inter-response time (IRT) recording","Partial interval recording"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Inter-response time (IRT) recording measures the elapsed time between the offset of one response and the onset of the next response. Duration recording measures how long a single response lasts. Frequency recording counts the number of occurrences. Partial interval recording only notes whether a behavior occurred at any point during a set interval.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.1","id":9},
  {"num":10,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to write a behavioral definition for a client's aggression. Which definition best meets the standard for being observable and measurable?","options":["Aggression occurs when the client is angry or frustrated","The client displays aggressive tendencies when overstimulated","Any instance in which the client makes physical contact with another person using a closed or open hand, including hitting, slapping, or scratching","The client engages in aggression when denied access to preferred items"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A behavioral definition must describe what the behavior looks like in observable and measurable terms. Option C defines aggression using physical, countable actions that any observer could reliably identify. 'Angry' and 'frustrated' are internal states that cannot be directly observed. 'Aggressive tendencies' and 'overstimulated' are neither observable nor measurable. Option D describes an antecedent condition rather than the behavior itself.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.5","id":10},
  {"num":11,"stem":"Which of the following is the most appropriate observable and measurable definition of on-task behavior?","options":["The student is engaged and paying attention","On-task: the student is seated, eyes oriented toward assigned materials or the instructor, and either writing or manipulating task materials","The student wants to complete the assigned work","On-task behavior reflects the student's level of motivation and effort"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An observable and measurable definition must describe physical behaviors that any observer could reliably see and record. Option B provides specific observable indicators (seated, eyes oriented, writing/manipulating materials). Options A and D reference internal states ('engaged,' 'motivation,' 'effort') that cannot be directly observed. Option C references an internal state rather than a physically observable behavior.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.5","id":11},
  {"num":12,"stem":"During a 30-minute session, an RBT recorded 12 instances of a client's calling-out behavior. What is the rate of calling out during this session?","options":["0.4 responses per minute","30 responses per minute","2.5 responses per minute","12 responses per session"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Rate is calculated by dividing the total number of responses by the time period: 12 responses ÷ 30 minutes = 0.4 responses per minute. Option B reverses the division. Option C is incorrect math. Option D reports total count (frequency), not a rate.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.6","id":12},
  {"num":13,"stem":"An RBT reviews a client's graphed frequency data over five consecutive sessions: 15, 12, 9, 7, 5. What trend does this data represent?","options":["An increasing trend","A decreasing trend","Variable data with no clear trend","A stable trend at low levels"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A decreasing trend is evident when data points consistently decline across successive sessions. The sequence 15, 12, 9, 7, 5 shows a clear and consistent decrease from session to session. The data is actively changing (decreasing), not stable.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.7","id":13},
  {"num":14,"stem":"An RBT has been inconsistently recording session data — sometimes recording every instance of the target behavior and sometimes only recording when they remember. Why is this a significant problem for the client's program?","options":["It reduces instructional time and makes sessions less efficient","It prevents the BCBA from making accurate, data-based decisions about the client's program","It violates HIPAA regulations related to client record-keeping","It may cause the client to engage in higher rates of problem behavior"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Reliable and consistent data collection is essential because the BCBA uses data to determine whether to continue, modify, or discontinue behavior programs. Inconsistent data creates an inaccurate picture of the client's progress or behavior, which can lead to inappropriate clinical decisions that may harm the client.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.8","id":14},
  {"num":15,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to conduct a paired stimulus preference assessment with a client. What does this involve?","options":["Presenting all available items at once and recording which one the client selects first","Presenting two items at a time and recording which item the client selects from each pair","Asking the client's caregiver to rank the client's preferred items from most to least preferred","Allowing the client free access to all items and recording how long they engage with each"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A paired stimulus (or forced-choice) preference assessment involves systematically presenting two items at a time and recording which item the client selects from each pair. Presenting all items at once describes a multiple stimulus assessment. Asking a caregiver to rank items is an indirect preference assessment. Allowing free access describes a free operant preference assessment.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.1","id":15},
  {"num":16,"stem":"An RBT is assisting with a preference assessment. The client consistently chooses the same item regardless of its position (left or right). What should the RBT do?","options":["Remove the preferred item from the assessment entirely","Ensure the items are rotated in position across trials as part of the standard procedure","Conclude the assessment and report the item as the most preferred","Replace all other items with new ones to test if the preference changes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"In a properly conducted preference assessment, items should be rotated in position (left/right) across trials to control for position bias. If the client consistently picks the item on one side regardless of what it is, position rotation helps identify whether the client truly prefers that specific item or simply has a side preference.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.1","id":16},
  {"num":17,"stem":"An RBT observes that a child consistently tantrums when asked to complete difficult math problems, and the tantrum stops when the math problems are removed. Which function of behavior does this most likely represent?","options":["Access to attention","Access to tangibles","Escape/avoidance","Automatic reinforcement"],"correct":2,"rationale":"When a behavior occurs in the presence of demands and results in the removal of those demands, the behavior is likely maintained by negative reinforcement in the form of escape or avoidance. Attention-maintained behavior typically occurs when attention is diverted. Tangible-maintained behavior involves gaining access to preferred items. Automatic reinforcement is maintained by internal sensory stimulation.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.3","id":17},
  {"num":18,"stem":"An RBT is helping the BCBA gather information for a functional behavior assessment. The BCBA asks the RBT to complete an ABC data collection form. What does ABC stand for?","options":["Assessment, Behavior, Consequence","Antecedent, Behavior, Consequence","Antecedent, Baseline, Condition","Analysis, Behavior, Contingency"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ABC stands for Antecedent (what happens before the behavior), Behavior (the specific behavior observed), and Consequence (what happens after the behavior). This is a descriptive assessment tool used to identify patterns related to the function of behavior.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.3","id":18},
  {"num":19,"stem":"A client's behavior plan states that the function of the client's screaming is access to attention. During a session, the client begins screaming while the RBT is working with another client. Based on the identified function, what is most likely the antecedent for this behavior?","options":["The client was asked to complete a difficult task","The RBT's attention was directed away from the client","A preferred toy was taken away from the client","The client is experiencing an internal sensory need"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Since the function of the screaming is access to attention, the antecedent that triggers the behavior is likely a situation where the client is not receiving attention. A difficult task as an antecedent would be more consistent with an escape function. Removal of a preferred item would be more consistent with a tangible function.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.3","id":19},
  {"num":20,"stem":"An RBT is conducting a free operant preference assessment. Which of the following best describes this procedure?","options":["The RBT presents two items at a time and records which one the client selects","The RBT asks the caregiver to list the client's favorite items and activities","The RBT provides access to a variety of items and activities and records which ones the client engages with and for how long","The RBT presents an array of items, removes the selected item, and re-presents the remaining items"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A free operant preference assessment involves providing the client with free access to a variety of items and activities while the observer records which items the client interacts with and the duration of engagement. Presenting two items at a time describes a paired stimulus assessment. Asking the caregiver describes an indirect method. Removing the selected item describes a multiple stimulus without replacement (MSWO) assessment.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.1","id":20},
  {"num":21,"stem":"An RBT is assisting a BCBA with an indirect functional assessment. Which of the following is an example of an indirect assessment method?","options":["Conducting an ABC observation during the client's school day","Interviewing the client's teacher about when the problem behavior occurs","Systematically manipulating environmental variables to test behavior functions","Recording antecedents and consequences in real time during a session"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Indirect assessment methods gather information about behavior through interviews, questionnaires, rating scales, and record reviews rather than direct observation. Interviewing the teacher is an indirect method. ABC observation is a direct (descriptive) assessment. Systematically manipulating environmental variables describes a functional analysis. Recording antecedents and consequences in real time is a direct observation method.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.3","id":21},
  {"num":22,"stem":"An RBT notices that a client frequently bites their own hand when alone with no one else present and no demands or tasks have been given. Based on this observation, which function of behavior is most likely?","options":["Access to attention","Escape from demands","Access to tangibles","Automatic reinforcement"],"correct":3,"rationale":"When a behavior occurs even when the individual is alone, with no social consequences (no attention, no escape from demands, no access to tangibles), the behavior is likely maintained by automatic reinforcement — the behavior itself produces sensory stimulation that is reinforcing. Attention-maintained behavior would require someone present. Escape-maintained behavior requires the presence of demands. Tangible-maintained behavior requires restricted access to a preferred item.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.3","id":22},
  {"num":23,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to assist with conducting a preference assessment for a nonverbal client with limited motor skills. Which type of preference assessment would be MOST appropriate?","options":["A verbal choice preference assessment where the client states their preference","A multiple stimulus without replacement assessment requiring the client to reach for items","An approach-based assessment adapted so the client can indicate preference through eye gaze","A written survey completed by the client"],"correct":2,"rationale":"For a client who is nonverbal and has limited motor skills, an approach-based assessment adapted to use eye gaze or other accessible response forms allows the client to indicate preferences despite their physical limitations. A verbal choice assessment requires the client to speak. Requiring the client to reach for items may not be feasible. A written survey requires literacy and motor skills the client may not possess.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.1","id":23},
  {"num":24,"stem":"A BCBA is conducting a curriculum-based skill assessment for a new client. What is the RBT's expected role in this process?","options":["To independently administer and score the full assessment and recommend targets","To assist the BCBA by administering assessment probes and collecting data as directed","To conduct the assessment and document a diagnosis for the treatment plan","To select skill acquisition targets based on the assessment results"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Per the RBT TCO (3rd ed.), RBTs participate in skill assessments under BCBA supervision by administering probes and collecting data as directed — they do not independently design, score, or interpret assessments. Conducting assessments independently and recommending targets is outside the RBT's scope. RBTs are not qualified to diagnose. Selecting skill targets is a clinical decision made by the supervising BCBA.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.2","id":24},
  {"num":25,"stem":"An RBT is teaching a child to request preferred items using a picture exchange system. The RBT presents a preferred item, waits for the child to hand over the corresponding picture card, and then immediately delivers the item. Which skill acquisition procedure is the RBT implementing?","options":["Discrete trial teaching","Naturalistic teaching","Mand training","Tact training"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Mand training involves teaching a client to make requests (mands) for preferred items or activities. The child is motivated by wanting the item and uses the picture card to request it — a mand is controlled by motivation and reinforced by receiving the specific item requested. Tact training involves labeling items, not requesting them.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.3","id":25},
  {"num":26,"stem":"An RBT is conducting a discrete trial with a student. The RBT presents a picture of a dog and says, 'What is this?' The student says 'Dog,' and the RBT provides praise and a small treat. Which component of the discrete trial served as the discriminative stimulus (SD)?","options":["The praise and treat","The student's response 'Dog'","The presentation of the picture and the question 'What is this?'","The inter-trial interval"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The discriminative stimulus (SD) signals the availability of reinforcement for a specific response. The picture of the dog combined with the question 'What is this?' serves as the SD. The praise and treat are the consequence (reinforcement). The student's response is the behavior. The inter-trial interval is the brief pause between trials.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.3","id":26},
  {"num":27,"stem":"An RBT is using a most-to-least prompting hierarchy to teach a child to wash their hands. On the first trial, the RBT provides full physical guidance. Over subsequent trials, the RBT gradually reduces the level of physical assistance. What is this process called?","options":["Prompt fading","Stimulus fading","Shaping","Chaining"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Prompt fading is the systematic reduction of prompts over time to transfer stimulus control from the prompt to the natural discriminative stimulus. Stimulus fading involves gradually changing the physical properties of a stimulus. Shaping involves reinforcing successive approximations of a target behavior. Chaining involves linking individual behaviors in a sequence.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.7","id":27},
  {"num":28,"stem":"A BCBA writes a program that involves teaching a child to brush their teeth by first teaching the last step independently (putting the toothbrush away) while providing full assistance for all prior steps. Once the child masters the last step, the second-to-last step is taught independently, and so on. Which procedure is this?","options":["Forward chaining","Backward chaining","Total task chaining","Shaping"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Backward chaining involves teaching the last step of a task analysis first while providing assistance for all preceding steps. Once the last step is mastered, the second-to-last step is taught, and so on. Forward chaining teaches the first step independently first. Total task chaining involves practicing every step of the task during each session.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.5","id":28},
  {"num":29,"stem":"An RBT is working with a client on tacting (labeling) common objects. The client correctly labels a 'cup' at the clinic table. However, when shown a different cup at the client's home, the client does not respond. What skill is the client lacking?","options":["Maintenance","Generalization","Fluency","Discrimination"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Generalization refers to the ability to perform a learned skill across different stimuli, settings, and people. The client can label one cup but not a different cup in a different setting, indicating a lack of stimulus generalization. Maintenance refers to performing a skill over time after training has ended. Fluency refers to the speed and accuracy of responding.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.8","id":29},
  {"num":30,"stem":"An RBT is using a token economy with a client. The client earns tokens for completing tasks and can exchange them for a preferred activity at the end of the session. The tokens function as what type of reinforcer?","options":["Unconditioned reinforcer","Conditioned reinforcer","Automatic reinforcer","Negative reinforcer"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Tokens are conditioned (secondary) reinforcers because they acquire their reinforcing value through repeated pairing with other reinforcers (backup reinforcers). Unconditioned reinforcers are naturally reinforcing without prior learning. Automatic reinforcement refers to behavior that produces its own sensory reinforcement. Negative reinforcement involves removal of an aversive stimulus.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.2","id":30},
  {"num":31,"stem":"An RBT is teaching a child to say 'ball' by first reinforcing 'ba,' then 'bal,' and finally 'ball.' Which procedure is the RBT using?","options":["Chaining","Shaping","Prompt fading","Discrimination training"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Shaping involves reinforcing successive approximations toward a target behavior. Chaining links together a series of discrete steps in a task analysis, not successive approximations of a single response. Prompt fading involves systematically reducing prompts. Discrimination training involves teaching a client to respond differently in the presence of different stimuli.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.10","id":31},
  {"num":32,"stem":"During a teaching session, an RBT delivers a prompt simultaneously with the instruction to ensure the client responds correctly on the first trial. What type of prompting procedure is this?","options":["Least-to-most prompting","Time delay prompting","Errorless learning (0-second prompt delay)","Most-to-least prompting"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Errorless learning with a 0-second prompt delay involves delivering the prompt at the same time as the instruction, ensuring the client responds correctly without errors. Least-to-most prompting starts with the least intrusive prompt and increases. Time delay involves waiting a set period after the instruction before delivering the prompt. Most-to-least prompting starts with the most intrusive prompt.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.7","id":32},
  {"num":33,"stem":"An RBT is teaching a client to identify colors. The RBT places a red card and a blue card on the table and says, 'Touch red.' The client touches the red card and receives praise. What type of training is this?","options":["Tact training","Mand training","Listener responding (receptive identification)","Echoic training"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Listener responding (receptive identification) involves the client responding to another person's verbal instruction by selecting or identifying the correct item. The client is not producing a verbal response but is demonstrating comprehension. Tact training involves the client labeling stimuli. Mand training involves teaching the client to request items. Echoic training involves the client repeating what someone else says.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.6","id":33},
  {"num":34,"stem":"An RBT is implementing a natural environment teaching (NET) procedure. During free play, the child reaches for a toy car on a high shelf. The RBT says, 'What do you want?' The child says, 'Car,' and the RBT hands the child the toy car. Which element best distinguishes this from discrete trial teaching (DTT)?","options":["The RBT provides a consequence after the response","The teaching occurs during a naturally occurring situation initiated by the child's motivation","The RBT uses a discriminative stimulus","The child receives reinforcement"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The key distinction of naturalistic teaching (NET) is that teaching opportunities arise from the child's natural motivation and interests in the moment, rather than being pre-planned by the instructor. Both NET and DTT involve delivering consequences after responses. Both use discriminative stimuli. Reinforcement is delivered in both approaches.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.4","id":34},
  {"num":35,"stem":"An RBT has been teaching a client to tie their shoes for several weeks. The BCBA now asks the RBT to probe whether the client can still tie their shoes without any additional teaching sessions. What concept is the BCBA assessing?","options":["Generalization across settings","Fluency","Maintenance","Stimulus control"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Maintenance refers to the extent to which a learned behavior continues to occur after teaching has been discontinued. By probing whether the client can still perform the skill without additional instruction, the BCBA is assessing maintenance. Generalization across settings would involve checking if the skill occurs in new environments. Fluency refers to accuracy and speed.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.9","id":35},
  {"num":36,"stem":"An RBT is teaching a child to answer social questions. The RBT asks, 'What is your name?' and the child responds with their name. This is an example of which verbal operant?","options":["Echoic","Mand","Tact","Intraverbal"],"correct":3,"rationale":"An intraverbal is a verbal response that is controlled by another person's verbal behavior, where the response does not match the verbal stimulus. The child hears a question and responds with a different word (their name). An echoic involves repeating the verbal stimulus. A mand is a request driven by motivation. A tact is a label of a nonverbal stimulus.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.3","id":36},
  {"num":37,"stem":"An RBT is teaching a child to make their bed using a task analysis. Each morning, the RBT has the child attempt every step of the task, providing prompts as needed for steps the child has not yet mastered. Which chaining procedure is this?","options":["Forward chaining","Backward chaining","Total task chaining","Behavior chain interruption"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Total task chaining (whole task presentation) involves the learner attempting every step of the task analysis during each session, with prompts provided for steps that are not yet mastered. Forward chaining teaches only the first step independently. Backward chaining teaches only the last step independently first.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.5","id":37},
  {"num":38,"stem":"An RBT delivers a highly preferred edible item immediately after the client correctly completes a task. Over time, the RBT begins delivering the edible after every other correct response, then every third correct response. What schedule-thinning process is occurring?","options":["Changing from a fixed ratio to a variable ratio schedule","Thinning from continuous reinforcement (CRF) to an intermittent schedule","Implementing differential reinforcement","Fading the reinforcer"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Moving from delivering reinforcement after every correct response (continuous reinforcement or CRF) to delivering it after every second or third response (intermittent schedule) is called schedule thinning. Fading the reinforcer would involve reducing its intensity or magnitude, not changing the schedule.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.1","id":38},
  {"num":39,"stem":"An RBT is teaching a child to imitate actions. The RBT claps their hands and says, 'Do this.' The child claps their hands and receives reinforcement. What type of prompt is the RBT using?","options":["Verbal prompt","Gestural prompt","Model prompt","Physical prompt"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A model prompt involves demonstrating the desired behavior for the client to imitate. A verbal prompt involves spoken instructions or hints. A gestural prompt involves pointing or motioning toward the correct response. A physical prompt involves physically guiding the client's body through the response.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.7","id":39},
  {"num":40,"stem":"An RBT is using a least-to-most prompting hierarchy. What is the correct order of prompts in this hierarchy?","options":["Full physical, partial physical, model, gestural, independent","Independent opportunity, gestural, model, partial physical, full physical","Verbal, visual, gestural, model, physical","Independent, verbal, model, full physical, partial physical"],"correct":1,"rationale":"In a least-to-most prompting hierarchy, the client is first given an opportunity to respond independently. If the client does not respond correctly, prompts are provided starting with the least intrusive (gestural) and progressively moving to more intrusive prompts (model, partial physical, full physical) until the client responds correctly.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.7","id":40},
  {"num":41,"stem":"An RBT notices that a client who learned to request 'juice' at the therapy table now also requests 'juice' at home and at school. This is an example of:","options":["Stimulus discrimination","Response generalization","Stimulus generalization","Maintenance"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Stimulus generalization occurs when a behavior learned in the presence of one stimulus also occurs in the presence of other similar stimuli or settings without additional training. Stimulus discrimination involves responding differently to different stimuli. Response generalization involves the emergence of untrained response forms. Maintenance refers to the behavior continuing over time.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.8","id":41},
  {"num":42,"stem":"An RBT is implementing a program where the client earns stickers for completing tasks and can trade in 5 stickers for 10 minutes of tablet time. What type of reinforcement system is this?","options":["Continuous reinforcement schedule","Token economy","Premack principle","Contingency contract"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A token economy is a reinforcement system where tokens (stickers) are earned for performing target behaviors and can later be exchanged for backup reinforcers (tablet time). Continuous reinforcement means delivering reinforcement after every instance. The Premack principle uses a high-probability behavior to reinforce a low-probability behavior without tokens.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.11","id":42},
  {"num":43,"stem":"An RBT is teaching a child to label the color 'red.' The RBT holds up a red card and says, 'What color?' The child says, 'Red,' and receives praise. Which verbal operant is being targeted?","options":["Mand","Tact","Intraverbal","Echoic"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A tact is a verbal operant in which the speaker labels or names something they can see, hear, smell, taste, or touch in their environment. The child sees a red card and labels it 'red,' which is a tact. A mand is a request. An intraverbal is a verbal response to verbal antecedents where the response does not match. An echoic involves repeating what someone else said.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.3","id":43},
  {"num":44,"stem":"An RBT is teaching a child to match identical pictures. The RBT places three pictures on the table and hands the child a picture that matches one of them. The child correctly places it on the matching picture. This is an example of:","options":["Identity matching (matching-to-sample)","Arbitrary matching","Receptive identification","Tact training"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Identity matching (identity matching-to-sample) involves matching identical stimuli. Arbitrary matching involves matching stimuli that are not physically identical. Receptive identification involves selecting an item in response to a verbal label. Tact training involves labeling stimuli verbally, not matching them.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.6","id":44},
  {"num":45,"stem":"During a teaching session, an RBT provides the instruction 'Touch your nose.' The client does not respond after 5 seconds. The RBT then provides a model by touching their own nose. The client imitates and touches their nose. The RBT provides praise. On the next trial, the client touches their nose independently after the instruction. What happened?","options":["The prompt was faded using a most-to-least hierarchy","The client demonstrated stimulus generalization","Transfer of stimulus control occurred from the model prompt to the verbal instruction","The client demonstrated response generalization"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Transfer of stimulus control occurred when the client's response shifted from being controlled by the model prompt to being controlled by the natural discriminative stimulus (the verbal instruction 'Touch your nose'). Stimulus generalization involves responding in new settings or to new stimuli. Response generalization involves performing untrained variations of a response.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.7","id":45},
  {"num":46,"stem":"A client's behavior intervention plan (BIP) specifies that the RBT should provide attention every 2 minutes regardless of whether the problem behavior is occurring. This is an example of which antecedent-based intervention?","options":["Differential reinforcement of other behavior (DRO)","Noncontingent reinforcement (NCR)","Differential reinforcement of alternative behavior (DRA)","High-probability instructional sequence"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Noncontingent reinforcement (NCR) involves delivering the reinforcer on a fixed-time schedule regardless of the client's behavior. DRO involves delivering reinforcement when the problem behavior has NOT occurred for a specified period. DRA involves reinforcing a specific alternative behavior. A high-probability instructional sequence involves presenting easy requests before a difficult one.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.2","id":46},
  {"num":47,"stem":"A BCBA instructs an RBT to reinforce any behavior the client engages in OTHER than self-injurious behavior (SIB) during 3-minute intervals. If no SIB occurs during the interval, the RBT delivers praise. Which procedure is this?","options":["Differential reinforcement of alternative behavior (DRA)","Differential reinforcement of incompatible behavior (DRI)","Differential reinforcement of other behavior (DRO)","Differential reinforcement of low rates (DRL)"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Differential reinforcement of other behavior (DRO) involves delivering reinforcement when the target problem behavior has not occurred for a specified time interval. DRA requires reinforcing a specific alternative behavior. DRI requires reinforcing a behavior physically incompatible with the target. DRL involves reinforcing reduced rates of the behavior.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.3","id":47},
  {"num":48,"stem":"An RBT is implementing extinction for a client whose screaming is maintained by attention. What should the RBT do when the client screams?","options":["Provide a verbal reprimand to the client","Redirect the client to a different activity","Withhold attention and do not respond to the screaming","Remove the client from the environment"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Extinction involves withholding the reinforcer that maintains the behavior. Since screaming is maintained by attention, the RBT should withhold attention. A verbal reprimand provides attention, which would reinforce the attention-maintained behavior. Redirecting involves giving the client attention. Removing the client from the environment is time-out, not extinction.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.4","id":48},
  {"num":49,"stem":"After implementing extinction for attention-maintained screaming, the RBT notices that the client's screaming initially increases in frequency and intensity before it begins to decrease. What is this phenomenon called?","options":["Spontaneous recovery","Extinction burst","Behavioral contrast","Response generalization"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An extinction burst is a temporary increase in the frequency, duration, or intensity of the target behavior when reinforcement is first withheld. Spontaneous recovery refers to the reappearance of a previously extinguished behavior after a period of time, not the initial increase at the start of extinction. Behavioral contrast refers to a change in behavior in one context due to reinforcement changes in another context.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.6","id":49},
  {"num":50,"stem":"A client's BIP states that when the client engages in aggression, the RBT should implement escape extinction by continuing to present the task demand. The client begins hitting the table and crying intensely. What should the RBT do?","options":["Remove the demand to calm the client down and try again later","Continue presenting the demand as specified in the BIP while ensuring safety","Implement a new intervention not included in the BIP","Leave the room to avoid reinforcing the behavior"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Escape extinction involves continuing to present the demand even when the problem behavior occurs. The RBT should follow the BIP as written while ensuring everyone's safety. Removing the demand would reinforce the aggression with escape. Implementing a new intervention is outside the RBT's scope. Leaving the room does not maintain the demand.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.4","id":50},
  {"num":51,"stem":"An RBT is working with a client whose behavior plan includes a high-probability instructional sequence before presenting difficult demands. What does this involve?","options":["Presenting several easy or preferred requests before delivering the difficult request","Providing reinforcement before the client has a chance to engage in problem behavior","Removing all demands and providing free access to preferred items","Gradually increasing the difficulty of instructions over multiple sessions"],"correct":0,"rationale":"A high-probability (high-p) instructional sequence involves presenting a series of easy or preferred requests that the client is likely to comply with immediately before presenting a more difficult or non-preferred request (low-p instruction). This builds behavioral momentum and increases the likelihood of compliance with the difficult request.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.2","id":51},
  {"num":52,"stem":"A client engages in elopement (running away) that is maintained by escape from demands. The BCBA designs a DRA procedure. Which replacement behavior would be the MOST appropriate to teach?","options":["Teaching the client to request a break using a communication card","Teaching the client to sit with hands folded","Teaching the client to engage in deep breathing exercises","Teaching the client to play with a fidget toy"],"correct":0,"rationale":"In DRA, the alternative behavior should serve the same function as the problem behavior. Since elopement is maintained by escape, the replacement behavior should be a more appropriate way to access escape — such as requesting a break. This gives the client a functional communication response that achieves the same outcome.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.3","id":52},
  {"num":53,"stem":"An RBT is implementing a behavior intervention plan for a client who engages in property destruction. During a session, the client picks up a chair. What should the RBT prioritize?","options":["Collecting data on the behavior before intervening","Implementing the extinction procedure as written in the BIP","Ensuring the safety of the client and others in the environment","Contacting the BCBA for immediate guidance"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Safety is always the top priority. When a client engages in behavior that poses an immediate risk (such as picking up a chair that could be thrown), the RBT must first ensure everyone's safety before focusing on data collection or specific BIP procedures.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.7","id":53},
  {"num":54,"stem":"An RBT is implementing an antecedent intervention by modifying the environment before a session. The RBT removes items that typically trigger problem behavior and arranges the workspace to minimize distractions. What type of intervention is this?","options":["Punishment procedure","Extinction procedure","Environmental modification (antecedent manipulation)","Consequence-based intervention"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Environmental modification is an antecedent-based strategy that involves changing the environment before the behavior occurs to reduce the likelihood of problem behavior. Punishment involves presenting an aversive stimulus after a behavior. Extinction involves withholding the reinforcer after behavior occurs. Consequence-based interventions are applied after the behavior.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.2","id":54},
  {"num":55,"stem":"A client's problem behavior has been on extinction for two weeks and has significantly decreased. One day, the behavior suddenly reappears at a high rate even though the extinction procedure is still in place. What is this most likely an example of?","options":["An extinction burst","Spontaneous recovery","Behavioral contrast","Stimulus generalization"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Spontaneous recovery is the temporary reappearance of a previously extinguished behavior after a period of time during which the behavior had decreased. An extinction burst occurs at the beginning of extinction when the behavior initially increases before decreasing, not after the behavior has already significantly decreased.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.6","id":55},
  {"num":56,"stem":"An RBT is implementing a DRI procedure for a client who puts non-food items in their mouth. Which replacement behavior would be MOST appropriate?","options":["Teaching the client to request a preferred food item","Teaching the client to keep their hands in their lap","Teaching the client to chew on an approved sensory chew toy","Teaching the client to sort objects into containers using both hands"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Differential reinforcement of incompatible behavior (DRI) requires reinforcing a behavior that is physically incompatible with the problem behavior — meaning the client cannot do both at the same time. Chewing on an approved sensory chew toy is incompatible with putting non-food items in the mouth because the mouth is already occupied.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.3","id":56},
  {"num":57,"stem":"An RBT implements a client's crisis plan during an episode of severe self-injurious behavior. After the episode, what should the RBT do FIRST?","options":["Resume the regular session as if nothing happened","Document the incident and notify the supervisor","Implement a punishment procedure to prevent future episodes","Discuss the incident in detail with the client's parent during pickup"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After a crisis event, the RBT should document the incident thoroughly and notify their supervisor as soon as possible. This ensures proper documentation and allows the BCBA to review and potentially modify the intervention plan. Resuming without documentation ignores the need for clinical review. Implementing a new punishment procedure is outside the RBT's scope.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.7","id":57},
  {"num":58,"stem":"An RBT is working with a client whose BIP includes a DRL (differential reinforcement of low rates) procedure for calling out in class. What does this mean the RBT should do?","options":["Reinforce the client only when they do not call out at all during the session","Reinforce the client when the rate of calling out is at or below a specified criterion","Reinforce an alternative behavior that replaces calling out","Ignore the calling out behavior completely"],"correct":1,"rationale":"DRL involves providing reinforcement when the behavior occurs at or below a pre-set criterion level. It is used when the goal is to reduce (but not necessarily eliminate) the frequency of a behavior. Reinforcing the complete absence of behavior describes DRO. Reinforcing an alternative behavior describes DRA. Ignoring the behavior completely describes extinction.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.3","id":58},
  {"num":59,"stem":"A client's BIP involves providing choices before presenting demands (e.g., 'Do you want to work on math or reading first?'). This is an example of which type of intervention?","options":["Consequence manipulation","Antecedent intervention (offering choices)","Differential reinforcement","Response blocking"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Offering choices before a demand is an antecedent intervention because it modifies the conditions that occur before the target behavior. Providing choices can increase the likelihood of compliance and reduce problem behavior by giving the client a sense of control.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.2","id":59},
  {"num":60,"stem":"A BCBA observes that a client's self-injurious behavior consistently increases when the BCBA leaves the room and decreases immediately when the BCBA returns and provides verbal praise. Which function is most likely maintaining this behavior?","options":["Escape/avoidance","Automatic reinforcement","Access to attention","Access to tangibles"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The behavior is evoked by the absence of attention (BCBA leaving) and maintained by the social attention provided when the BCBA returns. This is consistent with behavior maintained by access to attention. Escape-maintained behavior would decrease when demands are removed. Automatic reinforcement is maintained by internal stimulation.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.1","id":60},
  {"num":61,"stem":"A client's behavior intervention plan specifies that when the client engages in verbal aggression, one token is immediately removed from their token board. This procedure is designed to decrease the future likelihood of verbal aggression. This is an example of which procedure?","options":["Positive punishment","Negative punishment (response cost)","Extinction","Negative reinforcement"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Negative punishment involves the removal of a stimulus (the token, a conditioned reinforcer) contingent on behavior, with the goal of decreasing that behavior. This specific procedure is known as response cost. Positive punishment involves adding an aversive stimulus. Extinction involves withholding the reinforcer that was previously maintaining behavior.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.5","id":61},
  {"num":62,"stem":"After completing a therapy session, an RBT needs to write a session note. Which of the following is the MOST appropriate information to include?","options":["The RBT's personal opinions about the client's progress and family dynamics","Objective descriptions of behaviors observed, data collected, and programs implemented","A comparison of this client's performance with other clients on the caseload","Predictions about the client's future outcomes based on the RBT's intuition"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Session notes should contain objective, factual information including what behaviors were observed, what data was collected, which programs were implemented, and any notable events. Personal opinions, comparisons to other clients (a confidentiality breach), and intuition-based predictions do not belong in clinical documentation.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.4","id":62},
  {"num":63,"stem":"During a session, an RBT notices that the client has a new bruise on their arm that was not present at the previous session. The client's caregiver says the child fell at the playground. What should the RBT do?","options":["Accept the caregiver's explanation and continue the session without further action","Confront the caregiver and demand a more detailed explanation","Document the observation objectively and report it to their supervisor immediately","Take a photograph of the bruise to share with other team members"],"correct":2,"rationale":"RBTs are mandated reporters and must document any signs of possible abuse or neglect objectively and report their observations to their supervisor. Accepting the explanation without documentation or reporting could violate mandated reporting obligations. Confronting the caregiver is not appropriate and could compromise the client's safety.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.3","id":63},
  {"num":64,"stem":"An RBT realizes that they accidentally recorded data on the wrong data sheet during a session. What is the most appropriate course of action?","options":["Throw away the incorrect data sheet and pretend it did not happen","Cross out the incorrect entry with a single line, note the correction, and initial it, then record on the correct sheet","Use white-out to cover the incorrect data and rewrite it on the correct sheet","Wait until the end of the week to fix all data errors at once"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The appropriate way to handle documentation errors is to draw a single line through the incorrect entry (so it remains legible), write a brief note about the correction, initial and date it, and record the data on the correct sheet. Destroying data sheets compromises the clinical record. Using white-out obscures the original entry. Data corrections should be made as soon as possible.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.4","id":64},
  {"num":65,"stem":"An RBT has just completed a session in which the client exhibited a significant increase in self-injurious behavior compared to previous sessions. What should the RBT do?","options":["Wait until the next scheduled supervision meeting to mention it","Modify the behavior intervention plan independently to address the increase","Document the change in behavior and communicate it to the supervisor promptly","Only document the increase if it continues for three or more consecutive sessions"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Significant changes in client behavior should be documented and communicated to the supervising BCBA promptly, not delayed. The BCBA needs this information to make informed clinical decisions. Modifying the BIP is outside the RBT's scope. Waiting for multiple sessions delays necessary clinical oversight.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.1","id":65},
  {"num":66,"stem":"A parent asks the RBT for a copy of their child's session data to share with the child's school team. What should the RBT do?","options":["Provide the data directly to the parent since they are the client's legal guardian","Refer the parent to the supervising BCBA to handle the data sharing request","Tell the parent that data cannot be shared under any circumstances","Email the data directly to the school team since the parent requested it"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Requests for sharing client data with third parties should be directed to the supervising BCBA, who can ensure proper authorization (such as a signed release of information) is obtained and that data is shared appropriately while maintaining confidentiality. The RBT should follow the organization's procedures and involve the supervisor.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.3","id":66},
  {"num":67,"stem":"An RBT is documenting a client's session and needs to describe a tantrum that occurred. Which of the following is the MOST appropriate way to document the behavior?","options":["'Client had a terrible tantrum and was very upset and angry'","'Client was being manipulative and threw a tantrum to get attention'","'Client engaged in tantrum behavior (crying, falling to floor, hitting the table) for approximately 4 minutes following removal of the iPad'","'Client threw a fit because they did not get what they wanted'"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Documentation should be objective, specific, and measurable. This entry describes exactly what behaviors occurred (crying, falling to floor, hitting the table), the duration (approximately 4 minutes), and the context (following removal of the iPad) without subjective judgments or inferred motivations.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.4","id":67},
  {"num":68,"stem":"An RBT finishes a session and needs to enter data into the electronic data system. The RBT realizes they left their data sheet in the session room. What should the RBT do?","options":["Enter approximate data from memory into the system","Retrieve the data sheet and enter the actual data collected during the session","Skip the data entry for this session and double-count next session","Ask a colleague to estimate what the data might have been"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The RBT should retrieve the actual data sheet and enter the data that was actually collected during the session. Entering approximate data from memory is unreliable. Skipping data entry creates gaps in the record. A colleague who was not collecting the data cannot provide accurate information.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.4","id":68},
  {"num":69,"stem":"An RBT is updating the client's data graph and notices a significant downward trend in the target skill acquisition behavior over the past five sessions. What should the RBT do?","options":["Change the teaching procedure to something the RBT thinks might work better","Bring the data trend to the attention of the supervising BCBA during their next contact","Ignore the trend since short-term data fluctuations are normal","Reset the data and start graphing from the current session"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When data shows a significant trend, the RBT should communicate this to the supervising BCBA. The BCBA is responsible for analyzing data and making program modifications. Changing teaching procedures is outside the RBT's scope. Resetting data destroys the clinical record.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.1","id":69},
  {"num":70,"stem":"During a session, an RBT notices that a client's accuracy on a previously mastered skill has dropped significantly over the past three sessions. What should the RBT do?","options":["Continue running the program and assume the client is having a bad week","Immediately change the teaching procedure to address the performance drop","Document the data irregularity and bring it to the supervising BCBA's attention promptly","Skip the affected program until the client's performance improves"],"correct":2,"rationale":"When an RBT observes data irregularities or unexpected changes in client performance, they should document the findings and seek clinical direction from the supervising BCBA promptly. Clinical decisions — such as modifying a program — are made by the BCBA, not the RBT.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.2","id":70},
  {"num":71,"stem":"An RBT arrives at a client's home and learns from the caregiver that the client took a new medication for the first time this morning. The client seems noticeably drowsier than usual during the session. What should the RBT do?","options":["Cancel the session and reschedule because the medication may interfere with learning","Proceed with the full session as planned without mentioning it","Document the medication change and its apparent effects on the client and report it to the supervising BCBA","Call the prescribing physician directly to ask about the medication"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Variables that may affect client performance — including new medications, illness, or schedule changes — must be documented and reported to the supervising BCBA in a timely manner. This allows the clinical team to make informed decisions about the session and adjust the program if needed. The RBT's chain of command goes through the supervising BCBA, not directly to other professionals.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.3","id":71},
  {"num":72,"stem":"After a session, an RBT needs to document that a client required physical guidance to complete a self-care routine. Which of the following is the most appropriate session note?","options":["The client was really struggling today and needed a lot of help with hygiene","The client required full physical guidance for all 5 steps of the tooth-brushing task analysis","The client didn't want to brush their teeth, so the RBT had to physically force completion","The session went okay; the client was uncooperative but the RBT managed to get through the routine"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Professional session documentation must be objective, observable, and specific. Option B uses precise language (full physical guidance, all 5 steps, named task) that any reader could interpret consistently. Option A is vague and subjective. Option C uses inappropriate language ('force'). Option D uses evaluative terms ('uncooperative,' 'managed to get through').","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.4","id":72},
  {"num":73,"stem":"An RBT is implementing behavior skills training (BST) to teach a parent how to use a prompting procedure. Which of the following represents the correct sequence of BST components?","options":["Practice, instruction, modeling, feedback","Instruction, modeling, rehearsal, feedback","Modeling, feedback, instruction, rehearsal","Feedback, instruction, practice, modeling"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Behavior skills training (BST) follows the sequence: Instruction (describing the skill), Modeling (demonstrating the skill), Rehearsal (the learner practices the skill), and Feedback (providing corrective and positive feedback on the learner's performance). Practice should come after modeling, not before instruction. Feedback should come last.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.4","id":73},
  {"num":74,"stem":"An RBT is at a grocery store and sees one of their clients with the client's family. The family approaches and begins discussing the client's therapy progress in the store. What should the RBT do?","options":["Openly discuss the client's progress since the family initiated the conversation","Politely greet the family but explain that they cannot discuss therapy details in a public setting to protect confidentiality","Ignore the family completely and walk away","Provide a brief update since the conversation will be short"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The RBT must maintain client confidentiality at all times, including in public settings. Even though the family initiated the conversation, discussing therapy details in a grocery store could be overheard by others, compromising confidentiality. The RBT should politely redirect the conversation.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.5","id":74},
  {"num":75,"stem":"A parent offers the RBT a $100 gift card as a thank-you for their work with the child. What should the RBT do?","options":["Accept the gift card since the parent is being generous","Accept the gift card but report it to the supervisor","Politely decline the gift and explain that accepting gifts could create a dual relationship, then inform their supervisor","Accept the gift card but donate it to charity"],"correct":2,"rationale":"RBTs should avoid accepting gifts from clients or their families as it can create a dual relationship or the appearance of a conflict of interest. The appropriate action is to politely decline and explain the professional boundary, then inform the supervisor. Accepting a substantial gift crosses professional boundaries regardless of the giver's intentions.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.8","id":75},
  {"num":76,"stem":"A client's parent asks the RBT to change the client's behavior intervention plan because they think the current interventions are too restrictive. What should the RBT do?","options":["Modify the BIP to accommodate the parent's request","Explain to the parent that the RBT cannot change the BIP and refer them to the supervising BCBA to discuss their concerns","Ignore the parent's request and continue implementing the BIP as written","Agree with the parent and stop implementing the restrictive components"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Modifying a behavior intervention plan is outside the RBT's scope of practice. The RBT should acknowledge the parent's concern, explain that only the BCBA can modify the plan, and direct the parent to discuss their concerns with the supervising BCBA.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.2","id":76},
  {"num":77,"stem":"An RBT receives a friend request on social media from the mother of a current client. What is the MOST appropriate course of action?","options":["Accept the request to maintain a positive relationship with the family","Accept the request but limit what the parent can see on their profile","Decline the request to maintain professional boundaries","Block the parent so they cannot find the RBT's profile"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Accepting a social media friend request from a client's family member creates a dual relationship that crosses professional boundaries. The RBT should decline the request to maintain appropriate boundaries. Blocking is unnecessarily harsh; simply declining the request is sufficient and professional.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.7","id":77},
  {"num":78,"stem":"An RBT overhears a colleague discussing a client's private health information with another staff member who is not involved in the client's care. What should the RBT do?","options":["Join the conversation to provide additional information about the client","Ignore the situation since it is not the RBT's responsibility","Remind the colleague that discussing client information with unauthorized individuals is a confidentiality violation and report it to their supervisor","Post about the incident on social media to raise awareness about confidentiality"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The RBT has an ethical obligation to address confidentiality violations. They should remind the colleague that discussing client information with unauthorized individuals violates confidentiality requirements and report the incident to their supervisor. Joining the conversation further violates the client's confidentiality.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.5","id":78},
  {"num":79,"stem":"During a supervision meeting, the BCBA provides feedback that the RBT's prompting procedure was too intrusive and may be fostering prompt dependency. How should the RBT respond?","options":["Disagree with the feedback and continue using their current approach","Accept the feedback professionally and work with the BCBA to adjust the prompting procedure","File a complaint about the BCBA's feedback","Stop prompting entirely during the next session"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RBTs should respond to supervisor feedback professionally and collaboratively. Accepting the feedback and working with the BCBA to adjust the procedure demonstrates professional growth and commitment to best practices. Disregarding supervisor feedback undermines the supervisory relationship and may harm the client.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.9","id":79},
  {"num":80,"stem":"An RBT is working with a client whose family speaks a language different from the RBT's primary language. The RBT notices that communication with the family is difficult during parent training sessions. What is the MOST appropriate action?","options":["Continue the sessions and hope that communication improves over time","Inform the supervisor about the communication barrier so that appropriate supports (such as a translator) can be arranged","Cancel all parent training sessions until the family learns the RBT's language","Use online translation tools without informing the supervisor"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The RBT should inform their supervisor about the language barrier so appropriate supports can be arranged, such as a professional interpreter or translated materials. This ensures the family receives equitable and culturally responsive services.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.10","id":80},
  {"num":81,"stem":"An RBT is asked by a family friend to provide ABA therapy to their child on weekends privately, outside of the RBT's employment with an ABA company. What should the RBT do?","options":["Agree to provide services since it will help the child","Agree but only if the family pays in cash","Decline because RBTs must practice under the supervision of a BCBA and within a professional framework","Agree as long as the family signs a waiver"],"correct":2,"rationale":"RBTs must practice under the close, ongoing supervision of a BCBA. Providing ABA services independently, without proper supervision, is outside the RBT's scope of practice and violates ethical guidelines regardless of the relationship. A waiver does not override the ethical and professional requirement for BCBA supervision.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.3","id":81},
  {"num":82,"stem":"Which of the following activities is within the scope of practice for an RBT?","options":["Designing a new behavior intervention plan for a client","Conducting a functional analysis independently","Implementing a skill acquisition program as written by the supervising BCBA","Determining which assessments to administer to a new client"],"correct":2,"rationale":"RBTs are responsible for implementing programs and procedures as designed and directed by the supervising BCBA. This includes following skill acquisition plans, collecting data, and implementing behavior intervention plans with fidelity. Designing BIPs requires BCBA credentials. Conducting a functional analysis independently is outside the RBT's scope.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.2","id":82},
  {"num":83,"stem":"An RBT discovers that a colleague has been falsifying client data by recording higher performance scores than what actually occurred during sessions. What should the RBT do?","options":["Confront the colleague and demand they correct the data","Ignore it since it is not the RBT's client","Report the concern to the supervisor or through the appropriate reporting channels","Correct the colleague's data themselves without telling anyone"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Falsifying data is a serious ethical violation that can harm clients by leading to incorrect treatment decisions. The RBT has an ethical obligation to report this concern to their supervisor or through appropriate reporting channels. All professionals have a duty to report ethical violations regardless of whose client is affected.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.1","id":83},
  {"num":84,"stem":"An RBT's certification is about to expire. The RBT has not yet completed the required continuing education hours. What should the RBT do?","options":["Continue practicing and complete the hours after renewal","Let the certification lapse and continue working as an RBT","Complete the required continuing education hours before the expiration date and renew the certification on time","Ask the supervisor to waive the continuing education requirement"],"correct":2,"rationale":"RBTs are responsible for maintaining their certification by completing all requirements, including continuing education hours, before the certification expires. Allowing certification to lapse means the individual cannot legally practice as an RBT. The supervisor does not have the authority to waive BACB requirements.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.2","id":84},
  {"num":85,"stem":"An RBT posts on their personal social media page: 'So proud of my client who finally learned to tie their shoes today! I've been working with kids with autism for 3 years and I love this job!' What is the primary ethical concern with this post?","options":["RBTs should only post professional content on LinkedIn, not personal social media","The post could identify a specific client and disclose confidential information, and may constitute a misleading public statement about professional activities","It is unethical for RBTs to discuss their work experience on social media under any circumstances","The RBT violated HIPAA by mentioning they work with children with autism"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Describing a specific skill milestone may identify a client even without using their name, violating confidentiality requirements. Making public statements about professional activities — including framing personal accomplishments in a way that could misrepresent the RBT's role — is governed by ethics standards requiring compliance with requirements for public statements. The platform is not the central issue — the content is.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.6","id":85},
  {"num":86,"stem":"An RBT is measuring how many times a client says a peer's name during a 20-minute play session. Which measurement procedure is most appropriate?","options":["Momentary time sampling","Frequency/event recording","Partial interval recording","Whole interval recording"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Frequency recording counts each discrete occurrence of a behavior, making it ideal for countable events like vocal responses in a session. Momentary time sampling only checks whether the behavior is occurring at the end of each interval.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.1","id":86},
  {"num":87,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to measure the duration of each tantrum episode for a client. After measuring three tantrums with durations of 4 min, 7 min, and 3 min, what is the mean tantrum duration?","options":["3 minutes","4 minutes","4.67 minutes","7 minutes"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Mean duration = (4 + 7 + 3) ÷ 3 = 14 ÷ 3 = 4.67 minutes. Continuous duration recording captures the total time a behavior occurs.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.1","id":87},
  {"num":88,"stem":"An RBT is collecting latency data on a client's response to instructions. Latency is defined as the time between:","options":["The start of the response and the end of the response","The end of one response and the start of the next","The delivery of the antecedent stimulus and the onset of the response","The onset of the response and the next antecedent"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Latency measures the time elapsed from the presentation of the antecedent (e.g., instruction) to the beginning of the response.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.1","id":88},
  {"num":89,"stem":"An RBT divides a 30-minute session into 60 thirty-second intervals and marks whether the target behavior occurred at any point during each interval. This is:","options":["Whole interval recording","Momentary time sampling","Partial interval recording","Duration recording"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Partial interval recording scores an interval as positive if the behavior occurs at any point during the interval, regardless of duration or frequency.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.2","id":89},
  {"num":90,"stem":"An RBT checks whether a client is on-task at the end of every 2-minute interval during a 20-minute work period and records the result. This procedure is:","options":["Partial interval recording","Whole interval recording","Momentary time sampling","Frequency recording"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Momentary time sampling records whether the behavior is occurring at a specific moment (the end of the interval), not throughout the interval.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.2","id":90},
  {"num":91,"stem":"Which discontinuous measurement procedure tends to overestimate the occurrence of low-rate behaviors?","options":["Whole interval recording","Momentary time sampling","Partial interval recording","Duration recording"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Partial interval recording marks an interval as positive if the behavior occurs at any time during it, even briefly, which can inflate estimates for infrequent behaviors.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.2","id":91},
  {"num":92,"stem":"An RBT counts the number of math problems a student correctly completed on a worksheet after the session. This is an example of:","options":["Event recording","Permanent product recording","Interval recording","Latency recording"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Permanent product recording measures the tangible, observable outcome of behavior (the completed worksheet) rather than the behavior itself in real time.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.3","id":92},
  {"num":93,"stem":"A client is working on handwriting. The RBT photographs each completed writing sample at the end of each session. This is best described as:","options":["Continuous observation","Permanent product recording","Partial interval recording","Anecdotal observation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Photographing the completed writing sample is permanent product recording — measuring a durable outcome produced by the behavior.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.3","id":93},
  {"num":94,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to plot daily frequency counts of a client's vocal requests over a 3-week intervention. The most appropriate display is:","options":["Bar graph","Pie chart","Line graph","Scatterplot"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Line graphs connect data points across time and are the standard display for continuous behavioral data in ABA, allowing visual analysis of level, trend, and variability.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.4","id":94},
  {"num":95,"stem":"An RBT is graphing data and notices data points are steadily increasing across sessions. This pattern is best described as:","options":["High variability","A decelerating trend","An accelerating trend","A stable level"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A consistent upward movement of data points across sessions indicates an accelerating (increasing) trend.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.4","id":95},
  {"num":96,"stem":"An RBT records 8 correct responses out of 10 trials during a discrete trial session. What is the percentage of correct responses?","options":["70%","75%","80%","85%"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Percentage correct = (8 correct ÷ 10 total) × 100 = 80%. Accurate data entry and calculation are essential for progress monitoring.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.5","id":96},
  {"num":97,"stem":"After a session an RBT records frequency data in the client's data system but forgets to update the graph. The supervising BCBA is most likely to have difficulty with which of the following?","options":["Calculating IOA scores","Assessing current levels and trends to make treatment decisions","Determining the client's reinforcer preferences","Writing the behavior intervention plan"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Updated graphs allow BCBAs to visually monitor progress and make data-based decisions. Without current graphs, trend analysis and level changes are difficult to assess in a timely manner.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.5","id":97},
  {"num":98,"stem":"A teacher reports that a student 'has attitude.' An RBT's best response is to:","options":["Record 'has attitude' in the data sheet","Ask the teacher to describe specific observable behaviors the student exhibits","Accept the description since teachers know the student best","Report the concern to the client's parents"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Behaviors must be defined in observable and measurable terms. An RBT should assist in operationalizing vague descriptions so data collection is reliable and objective.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.6","id":98},
  {"num":99,"stem":"An RBT is unsure whether they are correctly implementing a data collection procedure. The best course of action is to:","options":["Continue collecting data and note the uncertainty in the session notes","Estimate the values based on prior sessions","Contact their supervising BCBA immediately for clarification","Skip data collection for that session"],"correct":0,"rationale":"RBTs should continue collecting data as best they can and promptly inform their supervisor of any uncertainty. This maintains data integrity while ensuring the supervisor can provide guidance.","domain":"A","domain_name":"Data Collection and Graphing","task":"A.7","id":99},
  {"num":100,"stem":"An RBT presents a client with two items at a time and records which item the client consistently selects. Over 10 trials, the client selects the red ball 9 out of 10 times when paired with other items. This is a:","options":["Free operant preference assessment","Single stimulus preference assessment","Paired stimulus (PS) preference assessment","Multiple stimulus without replacement (MSWR) assessment"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A paired stimulus (forced choice) preference assessment presents two items simultaneously and records selection. Consistent selection across pairings identifies high-preference stimuli.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.1","id":100},
  {"num":101,"stem":"An RBT places several toys in a room and observes which ones a client approaches and plays with during a free play period, without any instruction. This is a:","options":["Paired stimulus assessment","Multiple stimulus without replacement assessment","Free operant preference assessment","Single stimulus preference assessment"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Free operant preference assessments observe naturally occurring approach and engagement with items in an unrestricted environment, without presenting items in a structured sequence.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.1","id":101},
  {"num":102,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to complete an ABC data sheet during the next three sessions before the formal functional assessment begins. The PRIMARY purpose of this ABC data is to:","options":["Confirm the client's diagnosis","Identify possible antecedents and consequences associated with the problem behavior","Determine the client's reinforcer preferences","Document the frequency of the target behavior only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ABC (Antecedent-Behavior-Consequence) data collection is a descriptive assessment tool used to identify patterns and hypothesize the function of problem behavior before a formal functional analysis.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.2","id":102},
  {"num":103,"stem":"During a structured play session, an RBT notes that a client's self-injurious behavior (SIB) only occurs when preferred items are removed. The RBT should:","options":["Immediately implement a punishment procedure","Record the observation and report it to the supervising BCBA","Change the client's reinforcement schedule without consulting the BCBA","Ignore the behavior since it is not during instruction time"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Observational data suggesting an escape or tangible function should be accurately recorded and reported to the BCBA, who is responsible for interpreting assessment data and designing interventions.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.2","id":103},
  {"num":104,"stem":"During a functional analysis, an RBT is assigned to the 'alone' condition. In this condition the RBT should:","options":["Provide attention every 30 seconds","Leave the room or create a partition so the client has no social access","Deliver escape from demands contingent on problem behavior","Provide free access to preferred items throughout the session"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The alone condition in a functional analysis removes all social stimulation to test whether the behavior is maintained by automatic reinforcement. The RBT should minimize social interaction.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.3","id":104},
  {"num":105,"stem":"In the demand condition of a functional analysis, an RBT presents a task and removes it contingent on problem behavior. The purpose of this condition is to test whether the behavior is maintained by:","options":["Attention","Automatic reinforcement","Tangible reinforcement","Negative reinforcement (escape)"],"correct":3,"rationale":"The demand condition tests negative reinforcement (escape) as a maintaining function by making escape from tasks contingent on problem behavior.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.3","id":105},
  {"num":106,"stem":"A BCBA asks an RBT to administer a Verbal Behavior Milestones Assessment and Placement Program (VB-MAPP) probe. The RBT's primary role during this assessment is to:","options":["Score and interpret the results","Present assessment tasks exactly as directed and record responses accurately","Modify tasks based on the client's mood","Select which milestones to assess based on their experience with the client"],"correct":1,"rationale":"During skills assessments, RBTs administer probes according to the BCBA's directions and record data accurately. Interpretation and modification of the assessment protocol are the BCBA's responsibilities.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.4","id":106},
  {"num":107,"stem":"An RBT notices that a client performs a skill independently in the therapy room but not at home or at school. This is most relevant to which type of assessment?","options":["Preference assessment","Functional analysis","Generalization assessment","Skills acquisition probe"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Assessing whether skills occur across settings, people, and materials is a generalization assessment. The RBT should report this observation to the BCBA for consideration in treatment planning.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.4","id":107},
  {"num":108,"stem":"During a preference assessment, an RBT accidentally presents the same item three times in a row due to a shuffling error. The best course of action is to:","options":["Continue without noting the error, as preference data is informal","Discard all data from that session and start over immediately","Note the error on the data sheet and inform the supervising BCBA","Average the results across sessions and disregard the anomaly"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Procedural errors should be documented and reported to the supervisor. The BCBA can then determine whether the data are still usable or if the assessment should be repeated.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.5","id":108},
  {"num":109,"stem":"A parent tells an RBT that their child is 'being defiant.' For data collection purposes, the RBT should:","options":["Record 'defiance' as the target behavior on the data sheet","Operationalize defiance into specific, observable behaviors such as non-compliance with instructions within 5 seconds","Use a rating scale ranging from 1 (not defiant) to 5 (very defiant)","Ask the parent to count how many times the child was defiant each day"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Behavior must be defined in observable, measurable terms. Translating 'defiance' into specific, observable behaviors ensures reliable and objective data collection.","domain":"B","domain_name":"Behavior Assessment","task":"B.6","id":109},
  {"num":110,"stem":"An RBT presents a flashcard, waits for the client to respond, provides specific praise and a token for a correct response, records the result, and presents the next trial after a brief interval. This sequence describes:","options":["Naturalistic teaching","Discrete trial teaching (DTT)","Incidental teaching","Task analysis instruction"],"correct":1,"rationale":"DTT involves a clear antecedent (SD), a client response, a consequence (reinforcement or correction), and an inter-trial interval, repeated across multiple trials.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.1","id":110},
  {"num":111,"stem":"During DTT, a client responds incorrectly. According to standard DTT error correction, the RBT should:","options":["Ignore the error and immediately present the next trial","Provide the correct answer, prompt the correct response, reinforce the prompted response, then re-present the original trial","Apply a mild punisher and then re-present the trial","End the trial and provide a break"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Standard DTT error correction involves: (1) providing the correct answer, (2) prompting the correct response, (3) reinforcing the prompted response, and (4) re-presenting the trial to allow the client to respond independently.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.1","id":111},
  {"num":112,"stem":"An RBT follows a client's lead during play, waits for a communicative opportunity, and then prompts and reinforces appropriate requests using the client's chosen activity. This is an example of:","options":["Discrete trial teaching","Naturalistic/incidental teaching","Backward chaining","Token economy"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Naturalistic/incidental teaching embeds instruction within the client's naturally occurring activities and interests, using motivation from the environment to reinforce communication.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.2","id":112},
  {"num":113,"stem":"An RBT breaks down hand-washing into 12 sequential steps and teaches each step in order from step 1 to step 12. This approach is called:","options":["Backward chaining","Forward chaining","Total task presentation","Shaping"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Forward chaining teaches the first step in the sequence first, then each subsequent step in order, until the entire chain is mastered.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.3","id":113},
  {"num":114,"stem":"An RBT teaches a client to make a sandwich by first teaching the last step (placing the top slice of bread), then adding each preceding step one at a time. This is:","options":["Forward chaining","Shaping","Backward chaining","Total task presentation"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Backward chaining begins with the last step in a chain so the client always experiences completing the task, then works backward through the chain one step at a time.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.3","id":114},
  {"num":115,"stem":"An RBT physically guides a client's hand to write the letter 'A.' This is a:","options":["Gestural prompt","Model prompt","Physical prompt","Verbal prompt"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A physical prompt involves the RBT physically guiding or moving the client's body to produce the correct response.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.4","id":115},
  {"num":116,"stem":"An RBT points to the correct answer on a field of three pictures when asking a client a receptive identification question. This is a:","options":["Verbal prompt","Physical prompt","Gestural prompt","Model prompt"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A gestural prompt uses a physical gesture (such as pointing, nodding, or touching) to direct the learner toward the correct response.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.4","id":116},
  {"num":117,"stem":"An RBT gradually decreases the intensity of physical guidance over successive trials until the client responds independently. This procedure is called:","options":["Prompt delay","Graduated guidance / physical fading","Stimulus fading","Errorless learning"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Graduated guidance (physical fading) involves systematically reducing the intensity of physical prompts over time to promote independent responding.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.5","id":117},
  {"num":118,"stem":"An RBT waits 3 seconds after presenting an SD before delivering a prompt. If the client responds correctly within the delay, the RBT immediately reinforces. This is:","options":["Stimulus shaping","Constant time delay","Graduated guidance","Most-to-least prompting"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Constant time delay inserts a fixed pause between the SD and the prompt, giving the client an opportunity to respond before the prompt is delivered and gradually transferring stimulus control.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.5","id":118},
  {"num":119,"stem":"A client can label 'apple' when shown a red apple but not a green apple or an apple picture. To promote generalization, the RBT should:","options":["Only practice with the red apple until mastery is 100%","Vary the examples used during training across colors, sizes, and presentation formats","Use more intensive prompting with the red apple","Discontinue teaching 'apple' until generalization occurs naturally"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Training with multiple exemplars promotes stimulus generalization by exposing the client to varied instances of the concept.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.6","id":119},
  {"num":120,"stem":"After a client meets mastery criteria for a skill, the RBT gradually reduces the frequency of reinforcement while maintaining accurate performance. This procedure promotes:","options":["Acquisition","Generalization","Maintenance","Discrimination"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Thinning the reinforcement schedule after mastery promotes maintenance of the skill under natural reinforcement conditions.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.6","id":120},
  {"num":121,"stem":"A client cannot yet say 'water' but can vocalize 'wuh.' The RBT reinforces 'wuh,' then 'waw,' then 'wah-er,' and finally 'water.' This is an example of:","options":["Chaining","Fading","Shaping","Discrimination training"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Shaping involves reinforcing successive approximations toward a terminal behavior, gradually raising the criteria for reinforcement.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.7","id":121},
  {"num":122,"stem":"A client earns star stickers throughout the session and can exchange 5 stars for 3 minutes of preferred video time. This describes a:","options":["Fixed ratio schedule","Differential reinforcement procedure","Token economy","Behavioral contract"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A token economy uses conditioned reinforcers (tokens/stars) that are exchanged for backup reinforcers (preferred activities), allowing for consistent reinforcement delivery across varied tasks.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.8","id":122},
  {"num":123,"stem":"An RBT tells a class that if everyone earns at least 3 points during the lesson, the whole class gets 5 minutes of free time. This is an example of a:","options":["Independent group contingency","Dependent group contingency","Interdependent group contingency","Individual token economy"],"correct":2,"rationale":"In an interdependent group contingency, all group members must meet the criterion for the group to earn reinforcement.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.9","id":123},
  {"num":124,"stem":"An RBT practices a greeting skill with a client using multiple therapists and in multiple settings (clinic, home, community). This strategy is intended to promote:","options":["Acquisition","Maintenance","Generalization","Discrimination"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Practicing skills with multiple people and across multiple settings is a generalization programming strategy that promotes response generalization across stimulus conditions.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.10","id":124},
  {"num":125,"stem":"An RBT provides immediate, enthusiastic praise every time a client raises their hand to ask a question. Over the next week the hand-raising behavior increases. The praise is functioning as:","options":["A punisher","A negative reinforcer","A positive reinforcer","An extinction procedure"],"correct":2,"rationale":"When a stimulus is presented following a behavior and results in an increase in that behavior, it is functioning as a positive reinforcer.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.11","id":125},
  {"num":126,"stem":"A client spontaneously says 'cookie' when they see the cookie jar on the counter. This vocal response is under the control of a nonverbal stimulus and is reinforced by getting the cookie. This is a:","options":["Tact","Mand","Echoic","Intraverbal"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A mand is a verbal operant controlled by a motivating operation (MO) and reinforced by the specific item/action requested. The client's request is motivated by wanting the cookie.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.12","id":126},
  {"num":127,"stem":"An RBT holds up a picture of a dog and asks 'What is this?' The client says 'dog.' This verbal response is under the control of the nonverbal stimulus (picture) and is a:","options":["Mand","Echoic","Tact","Intraverbal"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A tact is a verbal operant controlled by a nonverbal stimulus (the picture of the dog) and generalized reinforcement.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.12","id":127},
  {"num":128,"stem":"In DTT, the inter-trial interval (ITI) serves which purpose?","options":["To deliver the consequence for the previous response","To provide a brief pause that helps the learner discriminate between separate learning opportunities","To give the RBT time to update the data sheet","To allow the client to access reinforcement"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The inter-trial interval separates trials, allowing the client to clearly distinguish each discrete learning opportunity and preventing confusion between consecutive stimuli.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.13","id":128},
  {"num":129,"stem":"An RBT demonstrates how to sort objects by color and then asks the client to do the same. The RBT's demonstration is a:","options":["Physical prompt","Gestural prompt","Model prompt","Textual prompt"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A model prompt involves the practitioner demonstrating the target behavior for the client to imitate.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.14","id":129},
  {"num":130,"stem":"An RBT reinforces only instances of a client's requests made with a full sentence and withholds reinforcement for one-word requests. This illustrates:","options":["Extinction","Shaping","Differential reinforcement","Variable ratio reinforcement"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Differential reinforcement involves reinforcing responses that meet a defined criterion while withholding reinforcement for responses that do not meet that criterion.","domain":"C","domain_name":"Behavior Acquisition","task":"C.15","id":130},
  {"num":131,"stem":"A client's problem behavior consistently occurs when preferred items are unavailable. The BCBA instructs the RBT to pre-teach a waiting skill and provide visual cues about when the item will be available. These strategies are:","options":["Consequence-based interventions","Antecedent-based interventions","Extinction procedures","Punishment procedures"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Antecedent-based interventions modify events that precede behavior to reduce the likelihood of problem behavior occurring, rather than addressing consequences after behavior occurs.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.1","id":131},
  {"num":132,"stem":"Before giving a client a non-preferred task, an RBT provides several easy tasks that the client completes successfully and praises highly. This strategy is called:","options":["Overcorrection","Behavioral momentum / high-probability request sequence","Noncontingent reinforcement","Response interruption and redirection"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A high-p (high-probability) request sequence uses several easy, highly reinforced tasks before presenting a low-probability (non-preferred) task to build momentum and increase compliance.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.1","id":132},
  {"num":133,"stem":"An RBT delivers a preferred item to a client every 5 minutes regardless of whether problem behavior occurs. This procedure is:","options":["DRO (differential reinforcement of other behavior)","DRI (differential reinforcement of incompatible behavior)","NCR (noncontingent reinforcement)","DRL (differential reinforcement of lower rates)"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Noncontingent reinforcement (NCR) delivers the maintaining reinforcer on a fixed or variable time schedule independent of behavior, which reduces the establishing operation for problem behavior.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.2","id":133},
  {"num":134,"stem":"An RBT reinforces a client for keeping hands in their lap (a behavior incompatible with hitting) and withholds reinforcement when hitting occurs. This is:","options":["DRO","DRI","DRL","DRA"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Differential reinforcement of incompatible behavior (DRI) reinforces a behavior that is physically incompatible with the problem behavior. Hands in lap is incompatible with hitting.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.2","id":134},
  {"num":135,"stem":"An RBT delivers reinforcement at the end of each 5-minute interval if problem behavior did NOT occur during that interval. This is:","options":["DRI","DRA","DRO","NCR"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Differential reinforcement of other behavior (DRO) provides reinforcement if the target problem behavior has not occurred during a defined interval of time.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.2","id":135},
  {"num":136,"stem":"An RBT is instructed to use extinction for attention-maintained problem behavior. The RBT should:","options":["Briefly explain to the client why the behavior is inappropriate","Redirect the client to another activity after each instance","Withhold attention following the problem behavior and continue the ongoing activity","Apply response cost after each instance of the behavior"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Extinction for attention-maintained behavior involves withholding the maintaining reinforcer (attention) following problem behavior. The RBT should not provide any attention (including verbal reprimands) contingent on the behavior.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.3","id":136},
  {"num":137,"stem":"When beginning extinction, a client's self-injurious behavior temporarily increases in frequency and intensity. The RBT should:","options":["Immediately reinforce the behavior to prevent injury","Consult the behavior plan; an extinction burst is expected and the plan should address safety","Stop the extinction procedure since it is making behavior worse","Implement a punishment procedure to suppress the behavior quickly"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An extinction burst (temporary increase in behavior) is expected when extinction is first implemented. The behavior plan should anticipate this and include safety protocols. The RBT should follow the plan and consult with the BCBA.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.3","id":137},
  {"num":138,"stem":"A client engages in severe self-injurious behavior that poses an immediate risk of harm during a session. The RBT's FIRST action should be to:","options":["Call the client's parents","Attempt to implement the behavior reduction plan as written","Ensure client safety and follow the crisis protocol as directed by the BCBA","End the session and complete an incident report"],"correct":2,"rationale":"In any crisis situation, the immediate priority is client safety. RBTs must be trained in and follow crisis and emergency procedures established by their supervising BCBA.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.4","id":138},
  {"num":139,"stem":"After a physical crisis management procedure is used with a client, the RBT must:","options":["Only document if the crisis resulted in injury","Complete an incident report and notify the supervising BCBA as soon as possible","Resume normal session activities without further action","Decide independently whether the event needs to be reported"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Any use of crisis management or physical restraint procedures must be documented via an incident report and reported to the supervisor, regardless of injury status.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.4","id":139},
  {"num":140,"stem":"A child's disruptive behavior occurs most frequently when the teacher is teaching a large group lesson and least frequently during one-on-one activities. The most likely function of this behavior is:","options":["Escape from demands","Tangible access","Automatic reinforcement","Attention"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Behavior that increases when adult attention is less available and decreases when individual attention increases is likely maintained by attention.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.5","id":140},
  {"num":141,"stem":"A client screams and throws materials when given worksheet tasks but is calm during free play. The MOST likely function of the screaming and throwing is:","options":["Tangible access","Attention","Escape from demands","Automatic reinforcement"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Problem behavior that occurs specifically when demands are presented and leads to removal of those demands is typically maintained by negative reinforcement (escape).","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.5","id":141},
  {"num":142,"stem":"A BCBA determines that a client's aggression is maintained by escape from tasks. The appropriate replacement behavior for the RBT to teach is:","options":["To sit quietly during tasks","To request a break using a functional communication response","To engage in a competing stereotypy","To self-monitor task completion"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Functional Communication Training (FCT) teaches a functionally equivalent, socially appropriate replacement behavior. Teaching the client to request a break serves the same function (escape) as the aggression.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.6","id":142},
  {"num":143,"stem":"A client's problem behavior escalates when the pace of instruction is very fast. An RBT adjusts the pacing by providing more frequent breaks between tasks. This is an example of:","options":["Consequence modification","Extinction","Antecedent manipulation","Response cost"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Modifying the pace of instruction is an antecedent manipulation that reduces the establishing operation for escape-maintained problem behavior by making the task environment less aversive.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.7","id":143},
  {"num":144,"stem":"An RBT is only permitted to implement punishment procedures when:","options":["The RBT personally decides the behavior warrants it","The procedure is written in the behavior intervention plan and approved by the BCBA","The client's behavior is disruptive to others","The punishment is mild and brief"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Punishment procedures must be approved and authorized by the supervising BCBA, written in the behavior intervention plan, and implemented only as specified. RBTs do not have independent authority to implement punishment.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.8","id":144},
  {"num":145,"stem":"A client's problem behavior has been reduced in the therapy clinic but still occurs at high rates at home. The RBT should:","options":["Consider the behavior reduced since it no longer occurs in the clinic","Report the discrepancy to the BCBA and document the observation","Train the parents to implement punishment at home","Add more sessions at the clinic to strengthen the reduction further"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Behavior reduction goals must generalize across settings. A discrepancy between clinic and home rates should be documented and reported to the BCBA, who can then adjust the plan to include generalization programming.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.9","id":145},
  {"num":146,"stem":"An RBT implements behavior reduction procedures across home, school, and clinic settings as directed by the BCBA. The purpose of this multi-setting approach is to:","options":["Increase billing hours","Promote generalization of behavior reduction across environments","Collect more data to confirm the function","Ensure the RBT receives sufficient supervision hours"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Implementing behavior reduction procedures consistently across multiple settings promotes generalization of behavior change beyond the training environment.","domain":"D","domain_name":"Behavior Reduction","task":"D.9","id":146},
  {"num":147,"stem":"After a session, an RBT writes in their session note: 'Client had a really bad day and was very aggressive.' The supervising BCBA is likely to ask the RBT to revise this note because it:","options":["Is too short","Contains subjective language rather than objective, observable descriptions","Does not include the client's diagnosis","Is missing the RBT's license number"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Session documentation must use objective, observable language. Words like 'really bad' and 'very aggressive' are subjective. The note should specify the frequency, topography, and context of behavior.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.1","id":147},
  {"num":148,"stem":"An objective session note that meets best practices should include:","options":["The RBT's personal interpretation of what caused the behavior","Observable descriptions of behavior, data collected, procedures implemented, and any notable events","A diagnosis of the behaviors observed","Recommendations for medication changes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Objective session notes document observable behaviors, data summaries, procedures used, client responses, and any significant events in non-interpretive, measurable terms.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.1","id":148},
  {"num":149,"stem":"During a supervision meeting, the BCBA provides corrective feedback about how the RBT is implementing a prompting procedure. The most professional response is to:","options":["Explain why the current approach is working fine","Accept the feedback respectfully, ask clarifying questions if needed, and implement the correction immediately","Complete the current program without changes and revisit the feedback at the next meeting","Report the feedback to the program director"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RBTs are expected to receive corrective feedback professionally, seek clarification when needed, and implement changes to their practice as directed by their supervisor.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.2","id":149},
  {"num":150,"stem":"A supervising BCBA sends an RBT written feedback after reviewing session notes. The RBT disagrees with one of the BCBA's suggestions. The appropriate action is to:","options":["Ignore the suggestion and continue with the original approach","Implement the BCBA's recommendation while raising the concern professionally in the next supervision meeting","Post about the disagreement on social media","Ask a colleague to side with the RBT"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RBTs should implement their supervisor's guidance while having professional conversations about disagreements through appropriate channels, such as scheduled supervision meetings.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.2","id":150},
  {"num":151,"stem":"During a session an RBT notices that a client has bruises in unusual locations that were not present at the previous session. The RBT must:","options":["Document it in session notes and mention it to the BCBA at the next scheduled supervision","Follow the organization's mandated reporter protocol and report the observation to the supervising BCBA immediately","Assume it is from normal play activity and take no action","Ask the client how the bruises occurred before reporting"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Unexplained injuries may indicate abuse or neglect. RBTs are mandated reporters and must immediately follow organizational and legal reporting protocols rather than waiting for the next scheduled supervision.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.3","id":151},
  {"num":152,"stem":"An RBT notices that a client is engaging in a new topography of self-injurious behavior not addressed in the behavior intervention plan. The RBT should:","options":["Implement a punishment procedure since the new behavior is clearly harmful","Ignore the new behavior until the BCBA updates the plan","Document the new behavior and report it to the supervising BCBA as soon as possible","Ask a colleague what to do"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Any new behaviors not addressed in the existing intervention plan should be promptly documented and reported to the supervising BCBA. The BCBA is responsible for updating the plan.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.3","id":152},
  {"num":153,"stem":"A client's parent asks an RBT during a session why their child's behavior program includes extinction. The appropriate response is to:","options":["Fully explain the rationale, research base, and all implementation details","Acknowledge the question, provide a brief, non-technical response, and offer to arrange a meeting with the BCBA for a thorough explanation","Tell the parent this information is confidential","Refer the parent to published research articles on extinction"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RBTs may provide general, supportive information to caregivers but should refer detailed clinical questions to the supervising BCBA. Arranging a meeting ensures the parent receives accurate, complete information.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.4","id":153},
  {"num":154,"stem":"A teacher asks an RBT whether they can change the reinforcement schedule for a student during the school day. The RBT should:","options":["Agree to the schedule change since the teacher knows the student","Make the change independently and inform the BCBA later","Explain that changes to the plan must be directed by the supervising BCBA and offer to relay the request","Tell the teacher the current schedule is fine without discussing with anyone"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Plan modifications must come from the supervising BCBA. The RBT should communicate the teacher's concern to the BCBA and facilitate the appropriate clinical decision-making process.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.4","id":154},
  {"num":155,"stem":"An agency requires all session notes to be submitted within 24 hours of service delivery. An RBT consistently submits notes 48-72 hours late. This is:","options":["Acceptable if the data are accurate","A violation of organizational requirements and potentially of billing and compliance standards","Only a concern if the BCBA requests the notes sooner","Not an issue since notes are eventually submitted"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Timely documentation is an organizational and regulatory requirement. Late session notes can affect billing compliance, treatment continuity, and supervisory oversight.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.5","id":155},
  {"num":156,"stem":"An RBT is asked to sign session notes written by another staff member for a session the RBT did not attend. The RBT should:","options":["Sign since it is just an administrative task","Refuse and report the request to a supervisor, as this constitutes falsification of records","Sign only if the notes appear accurate","Ask the client's parent for permission first"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Signing documentation for services not provided constitutes fraud and falsification of records. The RBT must refuse and report this request to a supervisor.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.5","id":156},
  {"num":157,"stem":"An RBT must maintain the confidentiality of client information. Which of the following would be a confidentiality violation?","options":["Discussing a client's progress in a supervision meeting with the BCBA","Sharing identifying client information with a friend who works in an unrelated field","Recording session notes in the agency's secure electronic records system","Telling a client's parent about their child's session data during a caregiver training"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Sharing identifiable client information with individuals who are not part of the client's treatment team without consent is a confidentiality violation under HIPAA and the BACB Ethics Code.","domain":"E","domain_name":"Documentation and Reporting","task":"E.5","id":157},
  {"num":158,"stem":"The BACB's RBT Ethics Code applies to RBTs:","options":["Only during direct client service hours","Only in interactions with clients and families","In all professional activities, including supervision, communication, and any conduct related to the role","Only when working with autistic clients"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The RBT Ethics Code governs all professional activities of an RBT, not limited to direct client contact. This includes supervision relationships, communications, and any activity related to the professional role.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.1","id":158},
  {"num":159,"stem":"An RBT who violates the BACB's Ethics Code may face which of the following consequences?","options":["A warning letter from the state board only","Suspension or revocation of their RBT certification by the BACB","A fine from their employer only","No consequences if the violation did not harm the client"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The BACB can impose sanctions including suspension or revocation of certification for Ethics Code violations. This is independent of any employer disciplinary action.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.1","id":159},
  {"num":160,"stem":"A supervising BCBA asks an RBT to implement a procedure that the RBT believes may be harmful to the client. The RBT should:","options":["Implement the procedure without question since the BCBA has more training","Refuse immediately and find a new employer","Raise the concern with the BCBA professionally; if unresolved, follow organizational escalation procedures","Implement the procedure but secretly document the concern"],"correct":2,"rationale":"RBTs have an ethical obligation to protect client welfare. Concerns about potentially harmful procedures should first be raised professionally with the BCBA; if unresolved, organizational or BACB escalation procedures should be followed.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.2","id":160},
  {"num":161,"stem":"An RBT's supervisor assigns more clients than the RBT can competently serve. The most appropriate action is to:","options":["Accept all clients to demonstrate work ethic","Inform the supervisor of the concern and document it; RBTs should not accept responsibilities beyond their competence","Serve all clients but reduce session duration","Ask a colleague to cover some sessions without notifying the supervisor"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RBTs must work within their scope of competence and inform supervisors when assignments exceed their capacity. Accepting responsibilities beyond one's competence risks harm to clients and violates ethical standards.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.2","id":161},
  {"num":162,"stem":"During a session, a client's sibling asks an RBT personal questions about the RBT's relationship status. The RBT should:","options":["Answer honestly to build rapport","Politely redirect the conversation to the session activities and maintain professional boundaries","Ignore the sibling and continue with the session without acknowledging them","Report the interaction to Child Protective Services"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RBTs must maintain professional boundaries with all individuals in the client's environment. Politely redirecting personal questions protects the therapeutic relationship and maintains appropriate professional conduct.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.3","id":162},
  {"num":163,"stem":"A client reaches out to an RBT on social media to ask questions about their sessions. The most ethical response is to:","options":["Respond to the questions since the client initiated contact","Accept the request and only discuss professional matters","Not accept the connection and inform the supervising BCBA; client communications must go through professional channels","Block the client without informing anyone"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Social media relationships with clients blur professional boundaries. RBTs should decline such contacts and inform their supervisor. Client communications should occur through established professional channels.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.3","id":163},
  {"num":164,"stem":"A client's parent offers an RBT a $50 cash gift at the end of the month as a token of appreciation. The RBT should:","options":["Accept the gift since it is not a large amount","Accept only if offered in private","Decline the gift and explain the organization's policy on gifts, consulting the supervisor if needed","Accept and donate the money to charity"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Accepting gifts from clients or their families can create dual relationships and conflicts of interest. RBTs should follow organizational policies regarding gifts and consult their supervisor. Most ethics codes discourage or prohibit accepting gifts.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.4","id":164},
  {"num":165,"stem":"An RBT has been working with a client's family for a year. The family invites the RBT to the client's birthday party. The RBT should:","options":["Attend since it is a social event, not a session","Consult the supervising BCBA about the dual relationship implications before making a decision","Decline without explanation","Attend but arrive late to minimize the appearance of a personal relationship"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Attending personal events with client families represents a potential dual relationship. RBTs should consult their supervisor before participating in any activities that extend beyond the professional role.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.4","id":165},
  {"num":166,"stem":"An RBT needs to implement a behavior reduction procedure in a public setting where peers may observe. The most important ethical consideration is:","options":["Speed of implementation","Ensuring the procedure is implemented exactly as written regardless of setting","Implementing the procedure in a way that minimizes embarrassment and preserves the client's dignity","Using the most restrictive procedure available"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Client dignity must be maintained in all settings. When implementing interventions in public, RBTs should consider how the procedure may affect the client's dignity and consult the BCBA about appropriate modifications.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.5","id":166},
  {"num":167,"stem":"An RBT is discussing a challenging session with a colleague in the clinic's common area where other families are present. This situation:","options":["Is acceptable since the colleague is also an RBT","Risks violating client confidentiality and dignity; case discussions should occur in private settings","Is appropriate as long as the client's name is not used","Is only a concern if the family overhears specific data"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Discussing case information in shared spaces where others may overhear violates client confidentiality and dignity. Case consultations should occur in private, secure settings.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.5","id":167},
  {"num":168,"stem":"An RBT witnesses a colleague implement a physical restraint incorrectly in a way that could have harmed the client. The RBT should:","options":["Address it directly with the colleague after the session without involving anyone else","Document the incident and report it to the supervising BCBA","Ignore it since it did not result in injury","Post about it anonymously on social media to raise awareness"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RBTs have an ethical obligation to report unsafe or unethical practices to their supervisor. Documenting and reporting the incident protects the client and initiates appropriate review and corrective action.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.6","id":168},
  {"num":169,"stem":"An RBT is approached by a journalist who wants to write a story about the client's progress. The RBT should:","options":["Share general information about ABA as a field","Decline to share any information about the client and refer the journalist to the appropriate administrator","Share information only if the journalist promises not to publish the client's name","Consult with the client's parents and then decide"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Client information is confidential. RBTs must decline all unauthorized requests for client information and refer media inquiries to administrative or clinical leadership who can address them properly.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.6","id":169},
  {"num":170,"stem":"An RBT has been under significant personal stress and finds it difficult to implement procedures with their usual accuracy and positivity. The ethical course of action is to:","options":["Continue working and not let personal issues affect professional responsibilities","Notify their supervisor of the issue so that appropriate support or schedule adjustments can be made","Take an unauthorized break during sessions","Ask a colleague to cover sessions without informing the supervisor"],"correct":1,"rationale":"RBTs must recognize when personal circumstances affect their professional performance and notify their supervisor. Proactive communication allows the organization to support the RBT and protect client welfare.","domain":"F","domain_name":"Ethics","task":"F.6","id":170}
];
